  "footnotes": [
    "Battle of Avarayr (451 CE): the Armenian nobility under Vard Mamikonian fought the Sassanid Persian army to defend Christianity; though militarily a defeat, it became the founding myth of Armenian national identity — the Sassanids eventually granted Armenia religious autonomy (Treaty of Nvarsak, 484); it is commemorated as a national holiday in Armenia",
    "Tigranes II 'the Great' (95–55 BCE): expanded Artaxiad Armenia into a brief empire stretching from the Caspian Sea to the Mediterranean, including Syria, Cilicia, and parts of Mesopotamia; after defeat by Lucullus and Pompey he became a Roman ally, but Armenia retained its kingdom as a Roman client state",
    "Kingdom of Cilician Armenia (1080–1375): Armenian nobles fleeing Seljuk conquest established a kingdom in Cilicia (SE Anatolia/NW Syria) that flourished through Crusader alliances; it was the last independent Armenian state before the modern republic, eventually destroyed by the Mamluk Sultanate",
    "Armenian Genocide (1915–1923): Ottoman authorities systematically deported and massacred the Armenian population; estimates of deaths range from 600,000 to 1.5 million; recognized as genocide by most historians and numerous states; the survivors formed diaspora communities across the Middle East, Europe, and Americas",
    "Artsakh (Karabakh) Melikdoms (c.1400–1822): five hereditary Armenian Christian principalities (meliks) in the Karabakh highlands maintained de facto autonomy under successive Turkmen, Safavid, and Qajar overlords; they conducted Armenian–Russian diplomacy and briefly resisted Persian authority in the 1720s with Russian encouragement",
    "First Republic of Armenia (1918–1920): the first modern Armenian state; fought border wars simultaneously with Georgia (over Lori) and Azerbaijan (over Karabakh/Nakhchivan); overwhelmed by the Red Army invasion in December 1920 and incorporated into the Transcaucasian SFSR"
  ]
}
